    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a very sharp question! You're absolutely right to question that, because mathematically, dividing the full $50,000 by 5 years *does* give you the same number ($10,000/year). But here's where the **soul** of accounting comes in, and why we absolutely *must* subtract the salvage value:\n\n**1. It's about the \"True\" Cost of Ownership**\nIf you just divide the $50,000 by 5 years, you are saying the machine is worth $10,000 *every single year*, even after the first year. That's mathematically correct for the *expense*, but it's financially impossible. A machine that's worth $10,000 a year after 5 years would be worth $50,000 a year after 1 year. That's not how depreciation works; it's a reflection of the asset's actual declining value.\n\n**2. The Salvage Value is the \"Floor\"**\nThink of the salvage value ($5,000) as the **floor** of the depreciation bucket. You can't depreciate the asset *",
